06308nam a22007935i 9789048550210DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20212021ne     fo  d z      eng d  a97890485502107 a10.1515/97890485502102doi  a(DE-B1597)612467  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anecNL 7aART0570002bisacsh00aLabour in a Single Shot :bCritical Perspectives on Antje Ehmann and Harun Farocki's Global Video Project /ced. by Gregory Williams, Peter Schwartz, Roy Grundmann. 1aAmsterdam : bAmsterdam University Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (410 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aFilm Culture in Transition00tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tAcknowledgements -- t1. Foreword: Eine Einstellung zur Arbeit/ Labour in a Single Shot -- t2. Labour in a Single Shot: Critical Perspectives - Editors' Introduction -- t3. Labour in a Single Shot - Antje Ehmann's Workshop and Exhibition Journals , 2011-2014 -- tHistory -- t4. Attitudes Towards Work : On the Historical Metamorphoses of Psychotechnology -- t5. One Shot, Two Mediums, Three Centuries -- t6. The Body and the Senses: Harun Farocki on Work and Play -- tPoetics -- t7. Ten Propositions -- t8. Videopoetics of Labour in a Single Shot -- t9. Knowing When to Be Wary of Images -- tEmbodiment -- t10. Punching In/Punching Out: Labour, Care, and Leisure at Work and at Play -- t11. Labour's Mediating Objects: Tools, Tactility, and Embodiment -- tNetworks -- t12. Database Labour: Supply Chains, Logistics, and Flow -- t13. Artwork and Artefact: The Networked Conditions of Labour in a Single Shot -- t14. Reading the Web Catalogue: Labour in a Single Shot as Online Environment -- tBibliography -- tIndex of Labour in a Single Shot workshop videos -- tGeneral Index0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aThis collection of essays offers a critical assessment of Labour in a Single Shot, a groundbreaking documentary video workshop. From 2011 to 2014, curator Antje Ehmann and film- and videomaker Harun Farocki produced an art project of truly global proportions. They travelled to fifteen cities around the world to conduct workshops inspired by cinema history's first film, Workers Leaving the Lumière Factory, shot in 1895 by the Lumière brothers in France. While the workshop videos are in colour and the camera was not required to remain static, Ehmann and Farocki's students were tasked with honouring the original Lumière film's basic parameters of theme and style. The fascinating result is a collection of more than 550 short videos that have appeared in international exhibitions and on an open-access website, offering the widest possible audience the opportunity to ponder contemporary labour in multiple contexts around the world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0https://www.aup.nl/en/publish/open-access  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aLabor in motion pictures. 0aLabor. 4aArt and Material Culture. 4aFilm Studies. 4aFilm, Media, and Communication. 4aMedia Studies. 4aTransnational and Global Studies. 7aART / Film & Video.2bisacsh  aVideo, documentary, labour, global, art.1 aBarker, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEhmann, Antje, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aElsaesser, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGatti, José, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGericke, Detlef, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrundmann, Roy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrundmann, Roy, ee